==English==
===Etymology===
Latin ''[[abhorrere]]''; ''ab'' + ''[[horrere]]'' to bristle, [[shiver]], [[shudder]]: compare French ''[[abhorrer]]''. See [[Horrid]]

===Transitive verb===
Imperfect and past participle: [[Abhorred]]<br>
Present participle: [[Abhorring]]

#To [[shrink]] back with [[shuddering]] from; to regard with horror or [[detestation]]; to feel excessive [[repugnance]] toward; to [[detest]] to extremity; to [[loathe]].
#:'''Quotations'''
#:*'''Abhor''' that which is evil; cleave to that which is good. - ''Romans 12:9''
#''(Obsolete):'' To fill with horror or [[disgust]].
#:'''Quotations'''
#:*It does '''abhor''' me now I speak the word. - Shakespeare, ''Othello, IV-i''
#''(Canon Law)(Obsolete):'' To [[protest]] against; to reject [[solemnly]].
#:'''Quotations'''
#:*I utterly '''abhor''', yea, from my soul Refuse you for my judge. - Shakespeare, ''Henry VIII, II-iv''

====Synonyms====
*To hate; [[detest]]; [[loathe]]; [[abominate]]. See [[Hate]].

===Intransitive verb===
#''(Obsolete):'' To [[shrink]] back with horror, [[disgust]], or dislike; to be contrary or [[averse]]; -- with ''from''. 
#:'''Quotations'''
#:*To '''abhor''' from those vices. - [[Udall]]
#:*Which is utterly '''abhorring''' from the end of all law. - [[Milton]]

